# Playwright E2E Testing Conventions — Ledger Live Desktop

> For shell permission requirements, see the `e2e-shell-permissions` skill.

## Write Boundary (CRITICAL)

**You MUST only write/modify files under these paths:**

- `e2e/desktop/` — test specs, page objects, fixtures, utils, userdata
- `libs/ledger-live-common/src/e2e/` — shared e2e enums, models, families, Speculos helpers

**You MUST NEVER modify application source code under `apps/`** with one exception:

- You MAY add `data-testid` attributes to React components in `apps/ledger-live-desktop/src/` when an element needed by a test has no testid. This is the **only** allowed modification to app source code.

Any other change to `apps/` (logic, styling, routing, state, etc.) is **strictly forbidden**.

## Design Principles

All E2E code must follow:

- **POM (Page Object Model)** — locators and interactions encapsulated in page objects, specs are thin orchestrators
- **DRY** — no duplicated locators, assertions, or setup logic; shared code goes in base classes, components, or fixtures
- **SOLID** — single responsibility per page object, open for extension via composition/inheritance, depend on abstractions (base classes)
- **Separation of Concerns** — specs contain only test flow orchestration; page objects contain only UI interactions and assertions; utils contain only infrastructure

## XRAY Ticket Requirement

Every E2E test **must** be linked to a Jira/Xray ticket (e.g., `B2CQA-XXXX`). Tests without a ticket reference are not accepted.

- The ticket key is passed via the `annotation` field: `{ type: "TMS", description: "B2CQA-XXXX" }`
- `addTmsLink(...)` must be called at the start of each test body
- After generating a test, the Jira ticket must be updated with a clear description of what the test validates

