## File & Naming

- Spec files: `kebab-case` with `.spec.ts` suffix — `add.account.spec.ts`, `send.tx.spec.ts`
- Page objects: `kebab-case` with role suffix — `account.page.ts`, `send.modal.ts`, `operation.drawer.ts`, `modular.dialog.ts`
- Components: `kebab-case` with `.component.ts` suffix — `layout.component.ts`, `drawer.component.ts`
- Fixture files: `common.ts` in `tests/fixtures/`
- Userdata fixtures: `kebab-case` JSON in `tests/userdata/` — `skip-onboarding.json`, `1AccountBTC1AccountETH.json`

## TypeScript Paths

`tsconfig.json` has `baseUrl: "."` so imports resolve from `e2e/desktop/`:

- Use bare `"tests/..."` imports: `import { test } from "tests/fixtures/common"`
- `~/*` maps to `apps/ledger-live-desktop/src/*`
- Shared e2e code: `import { Currency } from "@ledgerhq/live-common/e2e/enum/Currency"`

## Fixture System (`tests/fixtures/common.ts`)

Tests import `test` from `"tests/fixtures/common"` — **never** from `@playwright/test` directly.

The custom `test` extends `@playwright/test` with:

| Fixture            | Type                      | Default                          | Purpose                                             |
| ------------------ | ------------------------- | -------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------- |
| `lang`             | `string`                  | `"en-US"`                        | Locale                                              |
| `theme`            | `"light" \| "dark"`       | `"dark"`                         | Color scheme                                        |
| `userdata`         | `string?`                 | `undefined`                      | Name of JSON in `tests/userdata/` (without `.json`) |
| `speculosApp`      | `AppInfos?`               | `undefined`                      | Speculos nano app to launch                         |
| `settings`         | `Record<string, unknown>` | `{ shareAnalytics: false, ... }` | Settings merged into userdata                       |
| `featureFlags`     | `OptionalFeatureMap?`     | `undefined`                      | Feature flag overrides                              |
| `env`              | `Record<string, string>?` | `undefined`                      | Extra Electron env vars                             |
| `cliCommands`      | `CliCommand[]?`           | `[]`                             | CLI commands before test                            |
| `cliCommandsOnApp` | `{ app, cmd }[]?`         | `[]`                             | CLI commands requiring a specific Speculos app      |
| `simulateCamera`   | `string?`                 | `undefined`                      | Fake video for camera sim                           |
| `electronApp`      | `ElectronApplication`     | —                                | Launched Electron app                               |
| `page`             | `Page`                    | —                                | First Electron window                               |
| `app`              | `Application`             | —                                | Application facade (all page objects)               |
| `userdataFile`     | `string`                  | —                                | Path to the test's `app.json`                       |

The fixture chain is: `electronApp` → `page` → `app`.

Configure fixtures per `test.describe` block via `test.use({...})`:

```ts
test.describe("Add Accounts", () => {
  test.use({
    userdata: "skip-onboarding",
    speculosApp: currency.currency.speculosApp,
  });

  test(`[${currency.currency.name}] Add account`, async ({ app }) => {
    // ...
  });
});
```

## Page Object Model (POM)

All locators, interaction methods, and assertion methods live in page object classes.
Specs should **never** contain raw locators or direct `page.getByTestId(...)` calls.

### Base Classes (`tests/page/abstractClasses.ts`)

```ts
export abstract class PageHolder {
  constructor(
    protected page: Page,
    protected readonly electronApp?: ElectronApplication,
  ) {}
}

export abstract class Component extends PageHolder {
  // Shared dropdown/loader locators, waitForPageDomContentLoadedState()
}

export abstract class AppPage extends Component {}
```

### Page Object Pattern

- One page object class per page/view/modal/drawer/dialog
- Place under `tests/page/` (or `tests/page/modal/`, `tests/page/drawer/`, `tests/page/dialog/`)
- Private locators using `getByTestId` as primary strategy
- Public methods for actions and assertions
- Every public method **must** be decorated with `@step(...)` from `tests/misc/reporters/step`

```ts
import { expect } from "@playwright/test";
import { step } from "tests/misc/reporters/step";
import { AppPage } from "./abstractClasses";

export class PortfolioPage extends AppPage {
  private readonly balanceContainer = this.page.getByTestId("portfolio-balance");

  @step("Check portfolio balance is visible")
  async expectBalanceVisibility() {
    await expect(this.balanceContainer).toBeVisible();
  }

  @step("Open add account modal")
  async openAddAccountModal() {
    await this.page.getByTestId("portfolio-add-account-button").click();
  }
}
```

### Shared Components (`tests/component/`)

Cross-cutting UI elements (Layout, Modal, Drawer, Dialog) live in `Component` classes:

- `Layout` — sidebar and topbar navigation (`app.layout.goToAccounts()`, `app.layout.goToSettings()`)
- `Modal` — base modal interactions (`app.modal.close()`, `app.modal.continue()`)
- `Drawer` — base drawer interactions (`app.drawer.closeDrawer()`)
- `Dialog` — base dialog interactions (`app.modularDialog.closeDialog()`)

Specs call these directly via the `app` fixture.

### Application Facade (`tests/page/index.ts`)

Aggregates all page objects and components so specs access them via `app.<name>`:

```ts
export class Application extends PageHolder {
  public account = new AccountPage(this.page);
  public accounts = new AccountsPage(this.page);
  public layout = new Layout(this.page);
  public send = new SendModal(this.page);
  public speculos = new SpeculosPage(this.page);
  // ... 30+ page objects
}
```

Key properties: `portfolio`, `account`, `accounts`, `layout`, `send`, `addAccount`,
`receive`, `speculos`, `swap`, `settings`, `market`, `onboarding`, `drawer`, `modal`,
`modularDrawer`, `modularDialog`, `scanAccountsDrawer`, `operationDrawer`, `sendDrawer`,
`delegate`, `delegateDrawer`, `earnDashboard`, `liveApp`, `buyAndSell`, `ledgerSync`,
`password`, `settingsModal`, `assetDrawer`, `assetPage`, `analytics`, `swapDrawer`,
`marketBanner`, `fearAndGreedDialog`, `privateBalance`, `mainNavigation`, `redux`.

## Allure Reporting

### `@step()` Decorator (`tests/misc/reporters/step.ts`)

Every public method on a page object **must** be decorated with `@step(...)`. This wraps the method in `test.step()` for Allure reporting.

```ts
import { step } from "tests/misc/reporters/step";
```

### Static vs Dynamic Descriptions

- **Static** — for methods with no parameters or where params don't add context:

```ts
@step("Click Continue button")
async continue() { ... }
```

- **Dynamic** — use `$0`, `$1` positional placeholders for parameters:

```ts
@step("Select currency $0")
async selectCurrency(currency: Currency) { ... }
```

### Rules

- Every page object method **must** have a `@step(...)` decorator.
- Step descriptions are human-readable sentences describing intent (not implementation).
- When a method has basic-type parameters, use `$0`, `$1` positional placeholders.

## Selectors (Priority Order)

1. **`getByTestId`** — primary selector strategy. Rely on `data-testid` attributes.
2. `getByRole` — when testId is not available and element has clear ARIA role.
3. `getByText` / `getByPlaceholder` / `getByLabel` — last resort.
4. CSS/XPath — only when absolutely required (legacy selectors in existing code).

## Wait Strategy

- Default timeout is 120s per action (Electron + Speculos startup is slow).
- Use `await expect(locator).toBeVisible()` for element appearance.
- Use `locator.waitFor({ state: "visible" })` for dynamic content.
- **Never** use `page.waitForTimeout()` — no hardcoded timeouts.
- **Never** use `networkidle` or other deprecated Playwright APIs.

## Test Structure

### Data-Driven Tests

Tests are data-driven using arrays of test data with `for...of` loops:

```ts
const currencies = [
  { currency: Currency.BTC, xrayTicket: "B2CQA-2499" },
  { currency: Currency.ETH, xrayTicket: "B2CQA-2503" },
];

for (const currency of currencies) {
  test.describe("Add Accounts", () => {
    test.use({
      userdata: "skip-onboarding",
      speculosApp: currency.currency.speculosApp,
    });

    test(
      `[${currency.currency.name}] Add account`,
      {
        tag: ["@NanoSP", "@LNS", "@NanoX", "@Stax", "@Flex", "@NanoGen5"],
        annotation: { type: "TMS", description: currency.xrayTicket },
      },
      async ({ app }) => {
        await addTmsLink(getDescription(test.info().annotations, "TMS").split(", "));
        // Test body using app.<page>.<method>() calls
      },
    );
  });
}
```

### Tags

- **Device compatibility**: `@NanoSP`, `@LNS`, `@NanoX`, `@Stax`, `@Flex`, `@NanoGen5`
- **Currency**: `@ethereum`, `@bitcoin`, `@<currency_id>`
- **Family**: `@family-evm`, `@family-bitcoin`, `@family-<family>`
- **Priority**: `@smoke`

### Annotations

- Jira/Xray TMS: `{ type: "TMS", description: "B2CQA-XXXX, B2CQA-YYYY" }`
- Always call `addTmsLink(...)` at the start of each test

### Spec Conventions

- Specs are thin orchestrators: they call page object methods, never raw Playwright APIs.
- Access everything via the `app` fixture: `app.portfolio`, `app.layout`, `app.send`, etc.
- One `test(...)` or multiple data-driven `test(...)` inside `test.describe` blocks.
- `test.describe` names the feature area (e.g., `"Add Accounts"`, `"Send flows"`).
- `test(...)` describes the specific scenario (e.g., `` `[${name}] Add account` ``).

## Speculos Integration

All tests in `e2e/desktop/` run with the Speculos device simulator (`MOCK=0`). There is no mock mode — every test exercises the full E2E flow including device interaction.

**Always set `MOCK=0`** when running tests.

Key files:

- `tests/utils/speculosUtils.ts` — `launchSpeculos(appName)` / `killSpeculos(deviceId)`
- `tests/page/speculos.page.ts` — Wraps `@ledgerhq/live-common/e2e/speculos` functions (signing, address verification)
- `libs/ledger-live-common/src/e2e/families/` — Per-family device interaction flows

## Electron App

- Launched via `tests/utils/electronUtils.ts`
- Points to the webpack bundle at `apps/ledger-live-desktop/.webpack/main.bundle.js`
- Each test gets an isolated user data directory under `tests/artifacts/userdata/<uuid>/`
- Artifacts on failure: screenshots (app + Speculos device), video, console logs, network logs

## Userdata Fixtures (`tests/userdata/`)

Pre-built JSON files seed app state. Common fixtures:

- `skip-onboarding` — bypasses onboarding flow (no device info persisted)
- `skip-onboarding-with-last-seen-device` — bypasses onboarding **and** persists device info (`hasOnboardedDevice = true`)
- `1AccountBTC1AccountETH` — pre-loaded with BTC + ETH accounts
- `1AccountDOT` — pre-loaded with DOT account
- `speculos-tests-app`, `speculos-subAccount`, `speculos-x-other-account`

### Choosing the Right Userdata Fixture

| Scenario                                          | Fixture                                  | Why                                                                                                                                                                         |
| ------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Legacy portfolio (no feature flags)               | `skip-onboarding`                        | Legacy portfolio has no device-presence check                                                                                                                               |
| Wallet 4.0 (`lwdWallet40` enabled)                | `skip-onboarding-with-last-seen-device`  | The MVVM `Balance` component checks `hasOnboardedDevice`; without device info it renders `NoDeviceView` instead of `BalanceView`, and `portfolio-balance` will never appear |
| Tests that start from scratch (add account, etc.) | Match the portfolio variant being tested | See above                                                                                                                                                                   |
| Tests with pre-loaded accounts                    | Use a fixture that already has accounts  | `1AccountBTC1AccountETH`, etc.                                                                                                                                              |

## Wallet 4.0 (Feature Flag `lwdWallet40`)

Wallet 4.0 uses the MVVM architecture under `apps/ledger-live-desktop/src/mvvm/`. When `lwdWallet40` is enabled, several UI and navigation patterns change. Tests targeting Wallet 4.0 **must** account for these differences.

### Feature Flag Shape

```ts
featureFlags: {
  lwdWallet40: {
    enabled: true,
    params: {
      marketBanner: true,
      graphRework: true,
      quickActionCtas: true,
      mainNavigation: true,
    },
  },
},
```

### Key Differences from Legacy

| Aspect                      | Legacy                             | Wallet 4.0 (`mainNavigation: true`)                           |
| --------------------------- | ---------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Sidebar navigation          | `app.layout.goToAccounts()`        | `app.mainNavigation.openTargetFromMainNavigation("accounts")` |
| Portfolio balance rendering | Always renders `portfolio-balance` | Only renders when `hasOnboardedDevice && hasAccount`          |
| Userdata fixture            | `skip-onboarding` works            | **Must** use `skip-onboarding-with-last-seen-device`          |
| Add account flow            | Legacy modal (`app.addAccount`)    | May use modular dialog/drawer (`getModularSelector()`)        |

### Portfolio `Balance` Component Rendering (MVVM)

The `Balance` component (`apps/ledger-live-desktop/src/mvvm/features/Portfolio/components/Balance/index.tsx`) uses a three-way conditional:

1. `!hasOnboardedDevice` → renders `NoDeviceView` (no `portfolio-balance` testid)
2. `!hasAccount` → renders `NoBalanceView` (no `portfolio-balance` testid)
3. Both true → renders `BalanceView` (contains `portfolio-balance` testid)

**Pitfall**: Using `skip-onboarding` (which does NOT set `hasOnboardedDevice`) with `lwdWallet40` causes `portfolio-balance` to never appear, resulting in timeout failures.

### Modular Selector Pattern

In Wallet 4.0, the "add account" flow may use a modular dialog or drawer instead of the legacy modal. Use the `getModularSelector` utility to detect which variant is present:

```ts
import { getModularSelector } from "tests/utils/modularSelectorUtils";

const selector = await getModularSelector(app, "ASSET");
if (selector) {
  await selector.validateItems();
  await selector.selectAssetByTicker(currency.currency);
  await selector.selectNetwork(currency.currency);
  await app.scanAccountsDrawer.selectFirstAccount();
  await app.scanAccountsDrawer.clickCloseButton();
} else {
  await app.addAccount.expectModalVisibility();
  await app.addAccount.selectCurrency(currency.currency);
  await app.addAccount.addAccounts();
  await app.addAccount.done();
}
```

